# WebUI deployment environment variables.
#
# The 14 backends behind the WebUI split into two categories. Each gets
# its own base URL so a client bot deployment can read host content while
# still hitting its own local cluster/tickets/lan/projects.
#
# ── 1. Shared content (host = single source of truth) ──
#
# Backends: file browser, output static, reports, insights, zhihu cache,
# moments, qdrant explorer, daily stats, memory status.
#
# These represent knowledge accumulated by ONE bot. A client bot on
# another machine doesn't have any of this data, so it should cross-read
# from the host. Leave unset for same-origin (single-machine setup, or
# the host bot itself).
#
# Example — client bot reading host content:
# VITE_STATIC_SERVER_BASE=http://192.168.50.209:8889
#
# ── 2. Per-machine runtime state ──
#
# Backends: cluster, tickets, lan, projects (ProjectRegistry).
#
# Each bot has its own cluster jobs, its own tickets/ directory, its own
# LAN role, and its own ProjectRegistry pointing at THIS machine's source
# paths. The default (empty = same origin) is what every deployment wants
# almost always — the WebUI is served by the same bot that owns the local
# state, so same-origin Just Works.
#
# Only override this if you're running the WebUI dev server detached from
# the bot it should query (e.g. Vite dev on laptop, bot on a NAS).
#
# Example — detached dev server pointing at a remote bot for everything:
# VITE_STATIC_SERVER_BASE=http://192.168.50.209:8889
# VITE_LOCAL_API_BASE=http://192.168.50.209:8889
#
# Example — client bot WebUI (THIS is the recommended client setup):
# VITE_STATIC_SERVER_BASE=http://192.168.50.209:8889
# # VITE_LOCAL_API_BASE unset → cluster/tickets/lan stay same-origin (= the
# # client's own bot)
